00:40:33,719 --> 00:40:51,000
I mean, if it's true that he's the first one to come around and say you can have an unconditional commitment which gives you bliss and brings you together, and doesn't make you choose, like, remember the Greeks do, either let's satisfy the body part or let's satisfy the soul part.

430
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:52,520
This thing doesn't make you choose.

431
00:40:52,520 --> 00:40:54,839
It says you're essentially body and soul.

432
00:40:54,840 --> 00:40:59,400
You're essentially, and you can have both, even though they're contradictory.

433
00:40:59,400 --> 00:41:17,960
Then you see that there is some sense in which, on this Kierkegaard picture, Jesus has got to be the power that posited it, but posited this kind of self by saying, have an unconditional, and by what now?

434
00:41:17,960 --> 00:41:19,880
There's one little piece more missing, I think.

435
00:41:19,880 --> 00:41:26,520
