01:02:59,320 --> 01:03:01,400
He was addicted to computer games.

687
01:03:02,440 --> 01:03:05,839
He was, oh, I just want to go into all the profoundly detail.

688
01:03:07,280 --> 01:03:09,879
His life was a certain paradigm mess.

689
01:03:09,880 --> 01:03:20,800
And after a year of Buddhism and meditating and doing all these things that he's doing, he's completely clean of computer games and everything else.

690
01:03:21,119 --> 01:03:23,280
He's a super kid.

691
01:03:24,559 --> 01:03:25,520
What?

692
01:03:27,280 --> 01:03:30,159
Maybe a year and a half, but boy, is he throwing himself into it?

693
01:03:30,159 --> 01:03:31,440
He studies courses.

694
01:03:31,440 --> 01:03:35,599
He goes off to their retreats all by himself for 10 days.

695
01:03:35,920 --> 01:03:37,119
He gives up wine.

696
01:03:37,119 --> 01:03:38,320
He gives up meat.

697
01:03:38,400 --> 01:03:40,880
I mean, it's not trivial.

698
01:03:41,679 --> 01:03:43,440
And apparently, you could change.

699
01:03:43,520 --> 01:03:50,159
I mean, I'm amazed how much you can change a person if they find sort of the religion that's what they need.

700
01:03:50,159 --> 01:04:06,160
I mean, he was so, as long as we're putting all the family laundry on, he's the one who feels that his childhood was so miserable that he won't, unless we can change it, he was not going to do anything in the future that could make us happy.

701
01:04:06,159 --> 01:04:10,000
And now he's given up that attitude, and he loves to make us happy.

702
01:04:10,000 --> 01:04:17,439
And he sends email remembering far-off things in the past where he feels he did something that hurt us, and he apologizes we don't even remember.

703
01:04:17,759 --> 01:04:18,640
Okay.

704
01:04:19,520 --> 01:04:20,719
That's an ad for Buddhism.

705
01:04:20,719 --> 01:04:24,000
I give you an ad for Christianity now and an ad for Buddhism.

706
01:04:24,000 --> 01:04:25,840
But I saw another hand.

707
01:04:27,759 --> 01:04:28,800
Okay, yeah.

708
01:04:31,599 --> 01:04:32,960
Falls in love.

709
01:04:33,280 --> 01:04:37,520
Well, I wish I would, I'm eagerly waiting to see you.

710
01:04:38,480 --> 01:04:42,320
Maybe, maybe I'll bring you a report by the end of the semester.

711
01:04:44,239 --> 01:04:49,840
I don't think Buddhists fall in love, at least certainly not in the romantic way we do, because they'd be suffering.

712
01:04:50,320 --> 01:04:55,199
But they do something together and get married and have kids, so I don't know what to make of that yet.

713
01:04:55,320 --> 01:04:57,879
He'll give me lectures on it when the time comes.

714
01:04:58,920 --> 01:05:06,280
Okay, I want to go back to other left, what I call leftover issues.

715
01:05:06,280 --> 01:05:16,600
And the main leftover issue, this comes by office hours where 10, 12 people were beating up on me over mainly.

716
01:05:16,599 --> 01:05:21,240
But the hard thing to understand what God is in all this.

717
01:05:21,239 --> 01:05:28,039
And the first thing I want to tell you is don't worry about it and don't get all hung up about it in your papers.

718
01:05:28,039 --> 01:05:29,799
It's the phenomena that matters.

719
01:05:29,800 --> 01:05:38,039
Remember when Kierkegaard says that the lad is in love with the princess and he can't have her and it's about this that everything turns.

720
01:05:38,039 --> 01:05:46,360
That's the phenomena of all we've talked about, unconditional commitments, risk, resignation, faith, and so forth.

721
01:05:46,520 --> 01:05:57,959
But Kierkegaard is also trying to map his Regina experience onto this phenomenology of the lad and the princess, the sort of romantic love story.

722
01:06:00,039 --> 01:06:01,960
And it doesn't always work very well.

723
01:06:02,840 --> 01:06:09,320
But I'll try to put it, tell you how I see it, and try to put it together as best I can.

724
01:06:09,639 --> 01:06:21,800
So there is this problem of God is the, there is something called the absolute, and Abraham has an absolute relation to the absolute, which tells him to sacrifice Isaac.

725
01:06:21,800 --> 01:06:24,520
Now, Kierkegaard doesn't say this absolute is God.

726
01:06:24,520 --> 01:06:38,920
Kierkegaard doesn't say anything about God in fear and trembling, as far as I know, except that relating to God with love, like the Salentio does, is a kind of despair and is the wrong thing to do.

727
01:06:38,920 --> 01:06:43,520
But there are a lot of sort of god-like something or others running around in the book.

728
01:06:43,520 --> 01:06:47,680
And one of them is the absolute relation to the absolute.

729
01:06:47,679 --> 01:06:54,320
And then you get the puzzle that people say: but how can anything trump the unconditional commitment?

730
01:06:54,320 --> 01:07:03,120
How could there be this absolute coming in and saying, you have to sacrifice Isaac, you have to lose Isaac, you have to go against the ethical?

731
01:07:03,119 --> 01:07:11,120
Where does this get the authority to say those things if the unconditional commitment is the highest authority in your life?

732
01:07:11,119 --> 01:07:13,360
And Beatrice is your God person.

733
01:07:13,360 --> 01:07:14,239
Who can come in?

734
01:07:14,719 --> 01:07:18,319
How could anybody come in and say to Dante, you have to sacrifice Beatrice?

735
01:07:19,039 --> 01:07:21,520
And certainly Beatrice isn't going to say so.

736
01:07:21,520 --> 01:07:24,880
Well, then you have to think about it this way, I believe.

737
01:07:24,880 --> 01:07:44,240
God is something like there is some force, and I don't think it helps to call it God, but this absolute is the tells him to sacrifice Isaac, is the absolute opponent of his absolute commitment.

738
01:07:44,239 --> 01:07:53,359
That is, the absolute commitment comes up against something which says, you've got to be ready to give up Isaac.

739
01:07:53,360 --> 01:07:57,200
You've got to live in such a way that you can give up Isaac.

740
01:07:57,199 --> 01:07:59,919
That doesn't come from his absolute commitment.

741
01:07:59,920 --> 01:08:05,120
That's the only thing that his absolute commitment can't trump.

742
01:08:05,119 --> 01:08:11,679
God there, the absolute, that's making him sacrifice Isaac, is the sword hanging over the head of the beloved.

743
01:08:11,679 --> 01:08:21,279
I mean, it's the absolute fact that if you get committed to something finite, you're at the mercy of the vulnerableness of it.

744
01:08:21,280 --> 01:08:36,039
And that's the role, as far as I can see, that this absolute relation to the absolute, forcing Abraham to face the fact that you've got to be prepared to sacrifice Isaac, that's what it's better amount to.

745
01:08:36,999 --> 01:08:47,559
He better accept, that is Abraham, and integrate in his life the impossibility of a safe, stable, defining relation to whatever.

746
01:08:47,559 --> 01:08:51,320
Because there is no such thing as a safe, stable, defining relation.

747
01:08:51,320 --> 01:08:53,400
There's always the risk.

748
01:08:53,400 --> 01:08:58,759
And God is, or this absolute force, is the risk.

749
01:08:59,080 --> 01:09:03,319
Now, but there's more puzzling things which I want to talk about.

750
01:09:04,839 --> 01:09:14,679
How in the world can this absolute say that you should give up your defining relation?

751
01:09:14,679 --> 01:09:25,400
Not just that it could be taken away from you, but somehow there's an authority in your life that says you have to get rid of it right now.

752
01:09:25,400 --> 01:09:33,319
I mean, Abraham has to sacrifice Isaac right now, and Kierkegaard has to sacrifice Regina right now, that is, break his engagement.

753
01:09:33,320 --> 01:09:35,079
This is the anti-ethical part.

754
01:09:35,080 --> 01:09:42,119
I mean, that's different than the absolute coming in and saying Isaac might die is one thing.

755
01:09:42,120 --> 01:09:46,279
The absolute coming in and saying you have to do it.

756
01:09:46,280 --> 01:09:48,919
You have to break with your defining relation.

757
01:09:48,919 --> 01:09:50,839
What could ever tell you that?

758
01:09:50,839 --> 01:09:53,719
Your defining relation is the most important thing in your life.

759
01:09:53,719 --> 01:09:58,440
How could it or anything else tell you you have to break with your defining relation?

760
01:09:58,440 --> 01:10:06,679
Well, then I think it gets really murky, but in a very interesting way, you have to ask, well, what's the phenomenon?

761
01:10:06,679 --> 01:10:16,159
Well, it looks like there's some higher, truer calling, calling Abraham to sacrifice Isaac, but for what?

762
01:10:16,480 --> 01:10:18,480
One doesn't know.

763
01:10:19,120 --> 01:10:23,599
And Kierkegaard is sacrificing Regina for what?

764
01:10:23,919 --> 01:10:25,599
And he doesn't know.

765
01:10:25,919 --> 01:10:38,719
And it looks like what this is about, although Kierkegaard never says so, or I think wouldn't even admit it, is that it's saying you don't really have a defining commitment to Regina.

766
01:10:38,719 --> 01:10:48,159
There is something else that's calling you, some other destiny that you don't know yet, but it's already telling you, don't get involved with Regina.

767
01:10:48,160 --> 01:10:54,959
If you get married and have a wife and lots of kids, you won't be able to fulfill your calling.

768
01:10:54,959 --> 01:11:09,279
And something's calling Abraham, because he's trying always to complete this parallel, who is telling him, yeah, Isaac is important and being father of the faith is important, but something else you need to be true to is even more important.

769
01:11:09,280 --> 01:11:13,119
But certainly Abraham doesn't know what it is.

770
01:11:13,120 --> 01:11:16,079
But never mind Abraham, this is just a story.

771
01:11:16,080 --> 01:11:19,759
I think it's important that Kierkegaard doesn't know what it is.

772
01:11:20,080 --> 01:11:23,279
And there is some kind of phenomena like that.

773
01:11:23,280 --> 01:11:26,239
It's another case of doing what you can't understand.

774
01:11:26,639 --> 01:11:35,520
It's a special weird case of giving up what seems to be your identity in order to find out later, who you really are.

775
01:11:35,520 --> 01:11:40,879
It's something Kierkegaard can't really touch and deal with in here, but it's in the background somehow.

776
01:11:40,879 --> 01:11:51,440
Well, by that I mean Kierkegaard's going to turn out to be the greatest modern, the greatest Christian theologian since, I don't know, Luther, if he was a theologian.

777
01:11:51,440 --> 01:11:54,879
I mean, he's a very, very important thinker.

778
01:11:54,879 --> 01:11:56,679
He had a big deal mission.

779
01:11:56,679 --> 01:11:59,400
All existentialist stuff comes from him.

780
01:11:59,400 --> 01:12:04,839
And I don't think he could have done it with a bunch of kids running around and so forth.

781
01:12:04,839 --> 01:12:08,119
So, and he was doing something he didn't understand.

782
01:12:08,120 --> 01:12:27,319
He was giving up something which he felt was his defining relation, but he was doing it in a way which, if you look at it from later, which we're not allowed to do, remember, because he wasn't living later, but if you looked at it from later, you'd see Kierkegaard was really being called by a calling which trumped what looked like his other calling.

783
01:12:27,320 --> 01:12:29,959
I think that's how you have to think about it.

784
01:12:30,280 --> 01:12:31,879
And now let's see what else.

785
01:12:31,879 --> 01:12:34,279
I think maybe that's what I want to say.

786
01:12:41,160 --> 01:12:44,200
Yeah, all these other things have come up in the discussion anyway.

787
01:12:44,200 --> 01:12:46,199
Let me just keep looking at this.

