01:12:47,959 --> 01:12:48,679
Four minutes.

791
01:12:48,679 --> 01:12:50,279
I'll just touch on it.

792
01:12:50,280 --> 01:12:52,919
Can you have a defining commitment to the ethical?

793
01:12:52,919 --> 01:12:54,440
That came up a lot.

794
01:12:54,440 --> 01:12:55,959
That's a tough one.

795
01:12:56,759 --> 01:13:04,440
Having been beaten on for a while about that, I have a new idea, which I will run fast by you, that there are two different kinds of ethical.

796
01:13:04,440 --> 01:13:05,959
There's the Greek ethical.

797
01:13:06,440 --> 01:13:11,879
Agamemnon can't have a defining commitment to the ethical because being king is a role.

798
01:13:11,879 --> 01:13:17,799
And doing the ethical thing is a job that anybody could and should do who was king.

799
01:13:17,799 --> 01:13:22,360
And you can't get an individual definition out of doing your job as king.

800
01:13:22,360 --> 01:13:28,440
But since the Greeks didn't know anything about being individual, according to Kierkegaard, it's not a problem.

801
01:13:28,440 --> 01:13:31,159
Agamemnon did what he was supposed to do.

802
01:13:31,160 --> 01:13:36,919
He subsumed one ethical under a higher ethical and did his job as king.

803
01:13:37,240 --> 01:13:39,959
The issue comes with Martin Luther King.

804
01:13:40,080 --> 01:13:43,679
Martin Luther King is a very interesting, complicated case.

805
01:13:43,679 --> 01:13:50,879
When I introduced him into the discussion early on, it was as if, look at this guy, he's got an unconditional commitment.

806
01:13:50,879 --> 01:13:56,480
He's ready to die for justice for the black people here in the United States and now.

807
01:13:56,480 --> 01:13:57,440
And that's still right.

808
01:13:57,440 --> 01:13:59,759
That's exactly what he's doing.

809
01:13:59,759 --> 01:14:03,839
But what's interesting about it is it's sort of ethical, too.

810
01:14:04,080 --> 01:14:05,839
And I didn't mention it.

811
01:14:05,839 --> 01:14:09,119
Because what Martin Luther King is doing is intelligible.

812
01:14:09,120 --> 01:14:18,400
He's not in, it would look like, in the anguish of doing something absolutely disgusting, and he's doing something terrific.

813
01:14:18,400 --> 01:14:29,919
So he's not a good example, right off, of anybody going against the ethical, although he's a good example of having an unconditional commitment to something.

814
01:14:29,919 --> 01:14:30,639
Yeah.

815
01:14:31,599 --> 01:14:34,400
No, because, well, that's the right question.

816
01:14:34,400 --> 01:14:35,839
Is he a tragic hero?

817
01:14:35,839 --> 01:14:41,360
No, because there's something non-universal and individual about what he's doing.

818
01:14:41,360 --> 01:14:44,239
It's a category Kierkegaard didn't work out.

819
01:14:44,240 --> 01:14:47,360
I would like to give it as a paper topic, but I think it's too hard.

820
01:14:47,360 --> 01:14:54,959
Martin Luther King felt not that he was a king in the sense of Agamemnon King, he was a prophet.

821
01:14:54,959 --> 01:15:01,599
And prophets are called as individuals to do something now to the people.

822
01:15:01,999 --> 01:15:04,719
And there's a lot of unintelligibility in it.

823
01:15:04,719 --> 01:15:07,280
Why does it have to be Martin Luther King who does it?

824
01:15:07,280 --> 01:15:09,279
Why does it have to be done now?

825
01:15:09,280 --> 01:15:15,440
Why do you have to take the risk of killing white kids from the North to help the people in Alabama?

826
01:15:15,440 --> 01:15:20,320
